                    <div class="jonra" data-uuid="ce73df5bf96747ae8e7fdc0154729a82">
                        <h2 data-uuid="c60d94969e0043aaa5b67338a9e33cec"><span>Different Views on Texas Settlement</span><br />
                        </h2>
                    </div>
                    <figure class="green-star" data-uuid="acfd6a2b5a8f4b6e8b965fda0e4954e9"></figure>
                    <article class="column-container" data-uuid="7447986548214f96b6746d090a4ead07">
                        <div data-uuid="c2c6a196e707446aa83855071cad6d7b">
                            <p class="caption" data-uuid="1d55b6350dd24f85809237ae6bc73e63">Jos&#233; Maria Sanchez argued that Americans claimed Mexican-controlled land illegally.</p>
                            <p class="red hang" data-uuid="b2e78846646b4c0697fe889fbdc030ad">“The Americans . . . have taken possession of practically all of the eastern part of Texas, in most cases without the permission of the authorities. . . . They immigrate constantly finding no one to prevent them, and take possession of the [site] that best suits them without either asking leave or going through any formality other than that of building their homes.”</p>
                            <p class="source small" data-uuid="4875913e33ef4721836188b4c525b4d7">—attributed to Mexican soldier, Jos&#233; Maria Sanchez, April 1828</p>
                        </div>
                        <div data-uuid="d5b04cb13b7d4a31a563b69ea05e4c0e">
                            
                                <p class="caption" data-uuid="11aa559ebe874f9fbf400a1362ba70fc">Stephen F. Austin argued that Texas should be Americanized like its neighboring land.</p>
                            
                            <p class="blue-2 hang" data-uuid="b3f17119fd8f40f6935cf8c707f9cb48">“My object, the sole and only desire of my ambitions since I first saw Texas, was to . . . settle it with an intelligent, honorable, and [enterprising] people. . . . Texas should be effectually, and fully, Americanized—that is—settled by a population that will harmonize with their neighbors in the East, in language, political principles, common origin, sympathy, and even interest.”</p>
                            <p class="source small" data-uuid="8c083cdcc82f4428b9c0b3ae018756cd">—Stephen F. Austin, circa 1837</p>
                        </div>
                    </article>
