        <p data-uuid="28f96d80718d479c8172bdbb5ee1c8db">By 1834 Mexico came under the rule of General <b><dfn title="Santa Anna, Antonio L&#243;pez de">Antonio L&#243;pez de Santa Anna.</dfn></b> He soon suspended Mexico’s republican constitution and gave himself more power. To the already unhappy Texans, this was too much. They felt the time had come to fight for independence.<br />
        </p>
        <section data-uuid="ce7a9edaff78406a84cd312f31b5da12" class="section-a  biography">
            <div class="header-element" data-uuid="30f2e72d228140d0b4f3331cdf8eddbe">
                Biography
            </div>
            <p data-uuid="eb8b2ea7f7804a45bce1eb6b30e2022d" class="name">Antonio L&#243;pez de Santa Anna</p>
            <p data-uuid="09764ac1bdf345ef9899c0958332c5d3" class="date">1794 –1876</p>
            <figure data-uuid="994efefbc8d443eaa62dfc38ced9e66a" class="bio-image">
                <img alt="This is an artist's rendering of Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna in formal uniform." src="../../img/module_12_lesson01/8_snlese454170_335ap.png" data-uuid="1b705bfd320642f88fd093f70e7c1499" />
            </figure>
            <p data-uuid="36162410b4284a6cb1e382c4c15f9d5a">Antonio L&#243;pez de Santa Anna’s long military career began in 1810 at age 16. At first, he fought for Spain against Mexican independence. In 1821, though, he switched sides and supported the rebel forces. In 1832 Santa Anna led a successful revolt, and in 1833 he was elected president of Mexico. He promised to restore the Constitution of 1824. But he did not fulfill his promise, and war soon erupted.</p>
            <p data-uuid="3c6c33bd6bfe4b70998d01dd0a11e457"> Santa Anna continued to play a key role in Mexican politics for many years, but his disastrous leadership cost Mexico dearly.</p>
